riant of   Simmons  , with excrescent <i>-d</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Symmonds","meanings":["English: variant of   Symonds  ."]},{"name":"Simmons","meanings":["English (southeastern): variant of   Simon  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":22,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When William Symonds was born in 1360, in Lancashire, England, his father, Adam FitzSymonds, was 30 and his mother, Joan De Reppes, was 25. He married Lady Abigail Church in 1389. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1390, in his hometown, at the age of 30."},"et":{"1360–1390":"1360–1390","1361–1401":"1361–1401","1365–1420":"1365–1420","1390–1473":"1390–1473","1330–1370":"1330–1370","1335–1370":"1335–1370","1330":"1330","1473":"1473","1361":"1361","13